deck: Senketsu is a kamui in the form of a sailor uniform that Ryuko Matoi wears. He has the will of Ryuko's father but with little memory of its past.
description:
Origin

Kamui Senktesu was created by Dr. Isshin Matoi from Life Fibers in a secret lab under his mansion. He was created by splicing Ryuko Matoi's DNA into his construction. This would mean that only Ryuko could ever wear him effectively. Dr. Matoi died at the hands of Nui Harime the night he completed Senketsu, but managed to hide him away among the other cloth piled in the lab.

Creation

Senketsu (鮮血, Senketsu) is a main character of the Kill la Kill anime series that was produced by Trigger. It's directed by Hiroyuki Imaishi and written by Kazuki Nakashima. The character design was done by Sushio.

A tie-in manga series illustrated by Ryou Akizuki began on October 4, 2013 in Kadokawa Shoten's Young Ace magazine.

Major Story Arcs

Honnouji Academy

Senketsu was awoken when Ryuko had fallen into the lab, and her blood woke him form his sleep. In his desperation to stay awake, he forced himself on Ryuko. However, he had no real memory other than the image of his creator. He aided Ryuko in the rescue of Mako Mankanshoku from the Boxing Club Captain of Honnouji Academy, and together they faced off with yet more of the school's club captains as Ryuko tried to find the identity of her father's killer.

It wasn't until Ryuko was forced to battle Satsuki Kiryuin in Kamui Junketsu that she finally accepted Senketsu to fully synchronize with him. They did however lose in battle to both Tsumugu Kinagase and Uzu Sanageyama, one of Satsuki's Elite Four. This only served to increase their bond.

First Annual Naturals Election

As Satsuki was initiating the First Annual Natural Elections, Senketsu and Ryuko were set up to battle the Elite Four in turn. He was inspired by earlier witnessing Ira Gamagoori's secondary transformation that inspired him to do the same. He changed into a bladed version to defeat Gamagoori, flight and sound negation against Nonon Jakuzure, but their rematch with Sanageyama was interrupted by the appearance of Nui Harime. Harime's taunting of murdering Isshin drove Ryuko over the edge and Senketsu lost complete control. Satsuki tried to halt their rampage, but it took Mako to save them both.

Afterward, Ryuko was hesitant to wear Senketsu again and refused to get out of bed. Shinjiro Nagita, a former student of Honnouji Academy, attempted to encourage Ryuko to fight again. Though it seemed to work, Nagita revealed himself to be Nui in disguise. Unable to draw out any of his power, Ryuko lost this battle, and Nui sliced Senketsu into shreds. Her life was only saved by the appearance of Satsuki, but she also gathered up the pieces and distributed them among her forces raiding the Kyoto area.

Tri-City School Raid Trip

Ryuko was found by Aikuro Mikisugi. She was clutching only the scarf of Senketsu. They traveled to Kyoto to rip away the rest of his form from the Honnouji students, but the Seki Tekko, the final and most important piece, was in the hands of Satsuki. After wrenching it away, Ryuko and Satsuki held another epic battle through Osaka. This battle came to a draw.

Mikisugi finally explained into more detail about how Life Fibers are parasitic aliens and the role they played in humanity's evolution. Soon after, they left for Honnouji Academy to stop Satsuki and her mother, Ragyo Kiryuin from transforming the people of Honnou City into Life Fiber victims. Just as they arrived, Satsuki turned on her mother and declared open revolt.

Cultural & Sports Grand Festival

Ryuko reluctantly teamed up to fight Satsuki's mother, and Ryuko and Senketsu were able to break free when Ragyo tried to control them to fight Satsuki. In the chaos of the battle, Ragyo revealed that Ryuko must be the daughter she had previously experimented on in the past and thought to be dead.

Summer Break

After Satsuki attempted to kill Ragyo by blowing up the stadium, Senketsu pulled the unconscious Ryuko out by himself to Aikuro. They took her back to Osaka and into Nudits Beach's hidden base. For one month, Senketsu stayed by Ryuko's side as she remain asleep. She didn't wake up until several COVERS arrived in Osaka. However, the truth of her origins had driven her into a mad rage. She wanted nothing to do with Nudist Beach and swore to never wear Senketsu again. He couldn't prevent her from taking the bait of Ragyo's taunts to come after her.

Nudist Beach followed to Honnouji Academy to rescue Satsuki form captivity, and Ryuko followed after then and was being controlled by the influence of Junketsu. Satsuki teamed up with Senketsu to try and stop Ryuko's rampage aboard the Naked Sol. Their bond was makeshift at best, and Satsuki was suffering a great deal of strain to let him fight. He was eventually ripped from Satsuki, but leaped in to stop Nui from killing Mako. Once Satsuki broke open Junketsu's armor, Senketsu and Mako broke Ryuko's mind free to rip off the kamui and be reunited with Senketsu. They defeated Nui together, but he stopped her from following when Nui was saved by Rei Hououmaru.

Graduation Rebellion

With Junketsu altered with parts from Senketsu, Ryuko and Satsuki united their power to fight Ragyo atop the Original Life Fiber, but their mother's power was ftill far too much for the pair of them. By pretending to be killed by Ragyo, Senketsu and Ryuko broke into the the Original Life Fiber and destroyed the core. All that was left was defeating Ragyo, but she had a kamui of her own now, Shinra-Koketsu. With its power Senketsu and all Life Fibers couldn't move.

When he realized that Satsuki could hear his voice, it dawned on him that he could also break free of Ragyo's control. He burst into Ragyo and broke Rei Hououmaru from Shinra-Koketsu, thus halting the Absolute Submission field. They thought they had defeated Ragyo, but she escaped into space after Nui merged with the Original Life Fiber then fused with Shinra-Koketsu. Ryuko and Senketsu absorbed all the Life Fibers of the Honnouji Academy students and Junketsu to become Senketsu-Kisaragi and follow Ragyo.

During their battle in space, Ryuko purposefully took what could have been a fatal hit to max out their Life Fiber absorption to take over the Absolute Submission field. They were able to free humanity from the Life Fiber control, but Senketsu was starting to fall apart. He dragged Ryuko back to Earth, but was ultimately destroyed as he burned up shielding her from reentry.

Powers & Abilities

Kamui are clothing that is made from 100% Life Fibers, a parasitic alien organism. Senketsu was created specifically for Ryuko by Isshin Matoi. As such, only she can hear his voice. Though he appears to be an unusual high school sailor uniform, he can also transform into a set of armor that is even harder than steel. The only materials that can cut through Senketsu's Life Fibers are the Scissor Blade and Satsuki's Bakuzan.

The cost of this power is that Senketsu must drink Ryuko's blood to stay awake and transform. This used to require a great deal of blood, until she learned to fully synchronize with him and accepting him as part of her own skin. This is called Life Fiber Synchronize (人衣一体, Jin'i Ittai). He also has the ability to monitor much of Ryuko's body measurements and vital statistics.

Finishing Move: Sen-i-Soshitsu (Life Fiber Lost)

Senketsu is the only kamui that was specifically designed to be able to evolve through absorbing Life Fibers. This process is referred to as Sen-i-Soshitsu (戦維喪失, Sen-i-Sōshitsu). His evolution would eventually reach the point to where he could make himself understood by people other than Ryuko.

Senketsu Transformations

The powers of Kamui are far exceed those of the standard Goku Uniforms. As a Goku Uniform can have secondary transformation, so can Senketsu. He realized that he may have these abilities after witnessing Gamagoori's transformations. Only his forms aren't limited to only two.

Senketsu Senjin

Senketsu Senjin (鮮血閃刃, Senketsu Senjin）is the first secondary transformation of Senketsu. In this mode, Senketsu becomes the blade. He's covered in spikes and gives Ryuko three long claws on head hand. It was first revealed during her battle with Ira Gamagoori and used it to shred away the defenses of his Goku Uniform.

These blades are however not strong enough to cut Junketsu. He can also use this technique to form Ryuko's arms into blades, if her Scissor Blade is ever out of reach.

Senketsu Shippu

Senketsu Shippu (鮮血疾風, Senketsu Shippū）is the second transformation to be revealed. Senketsu transforms himself to create propulsion jets at Ryuko's lower half and allows her to flight and incredible speed. This was part of Ryuko's idea during her fight with Nonon Jakuzure.

Senketsu Mubyoshi

Senketsu Mubyoshi (鮮血無拍子, Senketsu Mubyōshi）is the third transformation where Senketsu essentially creates himself into a tuning fork. This was also used during the fight with Jakuzure to counter her sound wave attack.

Senketsu Shippu Senjin

Senketsu Shippu Senjin (鮮血疾風閃刃, Senketsu Shippū Senjin) is afourth transformation that is a combination of both Senketsu's flight and blade form. This technique was first used by Satsuki when she as wearing Senketsu to fight a mind controlled Ryuko.

Senketsu-Kisaragi

Senketsu-Kisaragi (鮮血更衣, Senketsu-Kisaragi) is the ultimate and final form of Senketsu. On top of having vastly superior power, this also allows for flight that can escape the upper atmosphere and into space. This form was manifested when Ryuko absorbed all the Goku Uniforms of the Honnouji Academy students and Satsuki's Junketsu.

Other Media

Anime

Kill la Kill (2013)

Kill la Kill (キルラキル Kiru ra Kiru) is the first original anime production created by Trigger, which was founded by two former Gainax employees in 2011. The series is directed by Hiroyuki Imaishi, Trigger co-founder; and written by Kazuki Nakashima. The first episode aired on October 3, 2010.

Senketsu's first anime appearance was in Kill la Kill - Episode 1 "If Only I Had Thorns Like A Thistle…". His character in the Japanese series was voiced by Toshihiko Seki.

deck: Son of Mayor William Dusk, he wanted more power than his father had, and turned himself into super-villain.
description:
The troubled son of Mayor William Dusk has been treated by Dr. Alan Bennett, the newly appointed head of the newly refurbished Arkham Asylum. Mayor Dusk was present during the re-opening of Arkham when he received a phone call. As soon as Dusk answered the phone call, a bio-electrical discharge surged straight to Dusk's pacemaker. Dusk died of a cardiac arrest within seconds.

Commissioner Gordon has Detective Eric Bullock do some digging around and he comes across something rather odd. The financial records of Susan Dusk, wife of the late Mayor, shows a large amount of money was being transferred monthly to a blind account for the last three years but the transfers stopped about two months ago. Bullock and Gordon question Susan about the money transfers. Mrs. Dusk tells Barbara that the account was kept private because her husband was having therapy sessions with Dr. Bennett.

Barbara is willing to give Dr. Bennett the benefit of the doubt since his father and Jim Gordon go way back. Dr. Bennett informs Barbara that the Mayor's interest in rebuilding Arkham and the therapy sessions were not meant for him but for his son Davis.

Davis was eventually captured and after a few months of rehabilitation, he was released from Arkham. During Davis' first few weeks of freedom, he was constantly met with fear and alienation. When Davis learned about the Justice Lords coming through to his world from a parallel dimension, he figured he could get his father back and make amends for the wrongs he committed.

Davis captures Dick Grayson and sends a message to Batman. Davis wants access to the portal that leads to the Justice Lords' dimension in exchange for Grayson's life. Grayson tells Rewire that Batman will never give in and in fit of rage, Davis implants an electro shock disc on Dick's chest. Batman arrives but Davis gets the upper hand on Terry. In the end, Dick attaches the electro shock disc to Rewire's chest and electro shock immobilizes Davis.

deck: The Polymath is a psychopathic villain from Absolution who has the ability to adapt to attacks.
description:
The Polymath is a villain from the Absolution series. His origins are largely unknown but he harbors a hatred for John Dusk who briefly crippled him.

Powers

The Polymath's powers is to adapt to things. Once something as harmed him his body learns to counter it. For example after being shot multiple times he became bulletproof, after jumping of cliffs he was eventually able to fly, by exposing himself to multiple injuries he gained a healing factor and so on.

During the time of Rubicon between the comics, Polymath went and harmed himself with everything he could thing of. He said he walked infront of a Semi-Truck, stood in explosions, shot, stabbed, and hit by Military grade weapons.

The powers he showed to have were:

  1. Super Strength: He could easily pick up and throw a bus without much effort. He could also throw cards around very easily.
  2. Invulnerability: Once he got shot, He became bulletproof, Once he got hit by an explosion he easily tanked having 3+ grenades exploding in his face with absolutely no effect. He was also able to tank a building busting explosion with no injury. He is also as durable on the inside as he is on the outside.
  3. Super Speed: He showed more speed then a regular human police officer.
  4. Flight: After jumping off cliffs a lot, Polymath eventually developed the ability to fly.
  5. Heat Vison: Unknown how he developed this power, His heat vison is enough to easily cut through buildings and destroy them with absolute ease. It was also able to easily cut through a car, and disintegrate people.
  6. Lightning Conjuration: After being struck by lightning, He became immune to it and developed the ability to shoot lightning out of his hands.
  7. Fire Conjuration: After being in Fire and Explosions, He gained the ability to emit fire out of his hands. He also showed the ability to emit fire out as an attack as a wide AOE.
  8. Poison Immunity: Polymath is immune to most poisons, but not all of them.
  9. Drug Immunity: After being put under by drugs, Once they took him off of it, They no longer worked.
  10. Suffocation Immunity: After being suffocated by John Dusk, Polymath no longer had to breathe.
  11. Healing Factor: After taking so much damage, His body developed a way to heal it all.
  12. Inside Immunity: It was stated that Polymath was as durable on the inside as he was on the outside.
  13. TP or Pre-Cog Immunity: Unknown to which one Happy Kitty has, Happy Kitty was unable to use her Pre-Cog or Telepathy on Polymath.
  14. Unknown Powers: Somehow, when Polymath was going to die because he was weakened by John Dusk by exposing him to a poison he had never took, Polymath could of unleashed a city wide destructive attack, but it would of taken him with it.
name: The Polymath

Gladius (グラディウス, Guradiusu is an antagonist in the One Piece series that was created by Eiichiro Oda. The series first began serialization in Shueisha's Weekly Shōnen Jump on August 4, 1997. He would later appear in the Punk Hazard Arc that began in Volume 66.

His first appearance was in One Piece Volume 69 CH. 682 "Mastermind".

deck: Private HIVE is a member of the H.I.V.E. Five and an enemy of the Teen Titans.
description:
Origin

Very little is known about Private HIVE's origin. He was probably raised in a military family or attended a military school. At some point he joined the HIVE Academy, from which he took his alias. He remained there until the Academy was destroyed by Cyborg. Following this, he briefly allied himself with a team of fellow former students, the HIVE Five, and later joined up with the Brotherhood of Evil.

Creation

Private HIVE was originally created for the Teen Titans animated television series. He made his first appearance in comics in Teen Titans Go! #26, written by J. Torres and illustrated by Mike Norton.

Major Story Arcs

Teen Titans Go!

Private HIVE appears as a member of the HIVE Five and as a freelance villain who occasionally clashes with the Teen Titans. He at one point acts as a champion fighter in gladiatorial battles arranged by the Lanista. He is contracted by his hero General Immortus to infiltrate the Titans Tower, but learns to his anger that he was merely being used as a pawn. In revenge he captures Immortus himself. He is approached to help form a new Fearsome Five, but refuses as he no longer wants to take orders. Later, calling himself Sergeant HIVE, he creates an army of runaways and street kids, the Army Brats, that he uses to commit crime. He is eventually defeated.

Powers and Abilities

Private HIVE has no known superhuman powers or abilities. He is at peak fitness, and is an exceptional hand-to-hand fighter. He wields a hexagonal shield that has a boomerang effect, always returning to him when thrown, which is done primarily as an offensive strike. He is also very knowledgeable about military protocol, and is a skilled tactician.

Other Media

Television

Teen Titans

Private HIVE appears as a minor villain in six episodes in this animated series, typically as a member of a villainous organisation. He made his first appearance in the episode "Deception," and his first major appearance in "Mother Mae-Eye." He was later frozen along with other villains in "Titans Together." He is voiced by Greg Cipes.
name: Private H.I.V.E.

deck: A haggish witch with candy-themed magical powers who tried to eat the Teen Titans.
description:
Mother Mae-Eye is a witch who appears in Teen Titans and Teen Titans Go! She uses her pies to cast illusions on people, then once they "love" her, she eats them.

Teen Titans (2003-2006)

Mother Mae-Eye appears in the episode "Mother Mae-Eye". The episode starts with the Teen Titans waking up and meeting Mother Mae-Eye who claims she is their mother. Mother Mae-Eye is then seen walking around the Titans Tower, transforming walls and furniture into candy and helping the Titans with different things, like putting Beast Boy's shoes on and combing Robin's hair. She makes the Titans dress up in coats, dresses, and raincoats when they have to go fight the H.I.V.E., embarrassing them.

Starfire, after getting hit in the head realizes Mother Mae-Eye is a witch and tries to warn the others but they won't listen. After finding this out, Mother Mae-Eye forces Starfire to eat more pies. Starfire does not get hypnotized because she has nine stomachs. Starfire then un-hypnotizes the other Titans. Cyborg says he bought a pie from an old lady, and the pie is what brought Mother Mae-Eye in. Mother Mae-Eye sends an army of gingerbread men after them but they end up defeating them and trapping her in a pie and giving her to the H.I.V.E. Five.

Teen Titans Go!

Mother Mae-Eye appears in the episode "Pie Bros" as owner of a pie store. Raven tells the other Titans the rumor that she bakes people in her pies, but the Titans laugh. Later Mother Mae-Eye captures Robin, Raven, and Starfire and tries to cook them.
name: Mother Mae-Eye
